76561198078463024,Recommended,218640,10065979,"Posted: 9 May, 2014",all,CupcakeCult,"Lucius is a devilish game that follows a little boy hellbent on murdering everyone in his house to please his father; Lucifer.The game is broken into chapters, and in each chapter you must kill an assigned target. There is no time limit to this, which gives you plenty of time to explore the game and interact with your fantastic surroundings, and talk to the characters which have unique dialogue that change as the story progresses.The game has some very difficult parts that take quite a bit of thinking, and a couple of easier parts. Sadly, each death is scripted and you have no choice in the way they die, which means if you replay the game, you don't get a different experience.Having said this, it is a wonderful little game, with some very interesting cutscenes. The premise is a little cliche, but the execution is fantastic, as it keeps you interested until the very end."
,Not Recommended,218640,25205066,"Posted: 28 August, 2016",all,Faithless,"It's obvious from the get go they took a lot of inspiration from the omen films for this game. Playing as a spawn of satan inside a very big mansion slowly killing its employees. All would be fine and dandy if this game offered you some choices and had some navigation system other than a map that only works when you're on one level on the mansion. It's a very big and unknown area and when you get your task you have to wander for who knows how long till you find the objective.Game is straightforward and linear, everything you do is predetermined. You can only achieve a kill in a specific way, and it's always the same which is very dull considering you wield different powers as you progress through the game. Basically, the bottom line is there is no replayability, there is if you like doing the same things over and over again without anything fresh. The ending can be seen from a mile away if you're familiar with the genre.NPC's are very badly programmed, their mouths won't move when they talk breaking the immersion and they will occasionally walk into a wall. This is especially horrid when you're on a mission and you have to interact with them, this will stop you from doing that.Also, there's some big bull*hit regarding 2 achievements in this game. One requires you to play for 20 hrs, other to play for 40. That wouldn't be a problem if the game wasn't, like I said before, linear. And if you have a private profile beware, because those hours, no matter how much you've spent in game won't be counted as long as your profile is private, you have to make it public to earn those achievements. This is the level of sh*t I honestly thought I'd never experience.All in all, it's a really bad game and if I could go back in time I'd probably give money to the homeless instead of supporting these devs."
