76561198089104979,Not Recommended,218640,17733783,"Posted: 26 August, 2015",all,Wirehead,"I got this game for 99 cents, which is good, because if I paid full price for it, I'd be angry. And the worst part about it is that the game had so much potential! I'm not against these kinds of stories. The Omen, The Exorcist, Rosemary's Baby, I own all three of them. Playing as Damien (I mean Lucius) should have been great!And for a while it was. The first few kills really did work, and I thought I got this game at a bargain. Loved the gore, too.Then it started sucking. Not the story. That part is good all around. I really enjoyed that aspect of it. And for a game like this, the visuals aren't terrible either. No, I'm talking about the quests themselves.Now, I'm not against difficult games. Far from it. But they sprinted across the line between difficult and next to impossible unless you know what to do next. For the majority of them, really. I appreciated the Ouiji board (first and last time I'll ever say that) for giving me the much needed clues to get a rough idea, but once I found my next victim, the game would basically go ""okay, kid, here's a giant mansion and a crappy map to get you through it. Go find this obscure item that you would have no reason to go looking for. Combine it with this other obscure item, then follow these contrived steps to get the kill.Now, this might have worked a little better if there were multiple ways to get a kill. And if the house were a little smaller. Not a lot, but just a touch. Then when you have no idea what to do, you don't have to spend half an hour looking through every room and drawer and hope you stumble across the next item. But nope, it's ""do this, then this, then this, then this.""Again, I'm not saying that I want the game to be easy. But I also don't want it so difficult that it's contrived.But I was willing to overlook all of that for the story. It really was interesting. Until...A game-breaking glitch.*sigh*So in one chapter, you have to kill a guy by using your fire powers to burn him to death. Like most video game bosses, he takes three hits. I fought him about five times, and this is how it went: 1. It worked fine, I just didn't have my strategy down. Fair enough. 2. I hit him, then he... disappears. You're in a small dungeon, so there's no place to hide. He just vanished, forcing me to re-start. 3. He's immune to your fire. 4. He's immune to fire. 5. He's immune to fire.At first I thought ""hey, I'm just missing. I mean, not sure how I can miss with a fireball bigger than I am, but whatever."" But repeatedly hitting him (in an area where the crosses were upside-down, mind you) with massive fireballs at point-blank range and not giving him a scratch lets me know, hey, this game is broken.I kinda want my 99 cents back. Difficulty bordering on being too contrived I can handle. It's irritating, but I can handle it. And they don't do it all the time. Sometimes you can figure it out with what they give you. But oftentimes I'd look up the solution, expecting to see something that made me go ""oh, I just missed that. Silly me"" and instead getting ""why on Earth would that be the next thing I do?""As a final note, something that amuses me about this game: the upside-down cross. I know it's a popular devil image and whatnot, but ironically so. It's supposed to be a symbol of defiance, but, if you read the history of it, it's actually a symbol of deep reverence and respect towards Jesus. The apostle Peter demanded to be crucified that way, as he didn't feel worthy of dying the same way his lord did. Just a funny note. I know symbols change and all that, but yeah.So overall, I'd give this game a 5/10. 5 for a great idea, decent visuals, good gore, some creativity, an a nice story, and -5 for... pretty much everything else."
