76561198122656542,Recommended,218640,32458183,Posted: 15 June,all,Darevries,"Lucius, a puzzle game where you are a little boy that enjoys casually killing members of his household. Also, Satan.This is a long composed review. If you’re too lazy to read everything just skip to the end and read the conclusion.It is the year 1966. A boy is born in the Wagner household; his name is Lucius. He lived peacefully as the son of a US senator in a mansion full of servants as a rather spoiled child. It is on his 6th birthday that things get interesting. And here is where the game begins.Lucius is a puzzle game where your objective is finding ways of killing people in your household without getting suspected. You have the entire mansion at your disposal, as well as some items you find around which you must figure out how to exploit for the mentioned purpose. You eventually gain too some supernatural powers that help you throughout the game. You know your victim; and now you must figure out the way of killing him or her.Although the overall concept of the story is really good and even unique, the game isn’t totally perfect. It is enjoyable, but I can’t call it a masterpiece for several reasons that do not do justice to its approach.First off, I would like to talk about the story. Personally, one of the things I appreciate the most in a videogame is a good story so I must mention this element first. And what I must say is, if you have this preference like me as well don’t expect a “true” story here; because the purpose of the game are the puzzles, and not the narration. The story, however, can be acceptable on this approach. A storyline is mostly absent through the game but it does have a narration by one of the characters; yet it is only about becoming aware of what a detective thinks of the extremely odd and confusing happenings at the house. The story is about learning about a child (Lucius) and how or why he does what he does in the game. And that’s mostly it. Nevertheless, if you don’t care much about stories and just want to get a game with great puzzles, don’t worry about this point. The story won’t let you down.Next, the aesthetics of the game are… very particular. I really like the style of the graphics and overall design. It really has the feel of a 1960’s old US mansion full of tragic events and confused people in despair. It has little shining elements over deep shadows, and it looks very good. The music blends almost perfectly with every surrounding, too.But then, let’s get to the main point: This game’s genre must be criticized. For the enthusiasts of this type of games, is Lucius a great puzzle game?The overall answer, and the main reason because I recommend this, is yes. Lucius is a very entertaining murder-puzzle game where finding out how to proceed to the next step of a murder or how to use a certain object to kill the designated victim in the end is truly satisfying. The game really has creative ways of fulfilling the objectives and once you get what the game wants you to do, you will feel really satisfied. Satisfied about being such a little genius and creative devil for murdering your family and getting away with it. Yep. However, because the game’s methods are so creative, you will constantly get your mind into a completely blank state not knowing what the heck to do in order to kill that single freaking person. The game lacks of any guide; which is good until the exact steps for proceeding the game get too specific for anyone to guess and you can’t possibly imagine what to do no matter how creative you are. The game does give you clues, however, they are practically useless. Let’s be completely honest: you will find yourself more than one time relying on walkthroughs in order to continue. Given the game’s circumstances, that’s completely natural, believe mebecause I myself did that as well once or twice.But that doesn’t mean the game is impossible to figure out. I mean, there are around 3 times when the answer is completely obvious and other times where you just keep walking in circles around all the mansion confused as hell. But overall, as I’ve already mentioned, puzzles can be figured out and when you do you feel ultimately satisfied. Even if the objective is the same all game and the chapters get repetitive, each killing method is always different from the previous.ConclusionLucius is a puzzle game where you must figure out the way of killing your victims without being suspected. For this, you have a whole mansion at your disposal with lots of items and some supernatural powers. The story is nothing impressive but it is okay; good thing is that it has a narration from one of the character’s perspective through the story. It has a nice visual style and fitting music. As a puzzle game, it is really good and truly entertaining and satisfying; however, the puzzles might get hard to guess at some points and the lack of any guide in the game is no help.Worth buying?If you want four to eight or so hours of thrilling puzzles and a not-too-complicated story you should definitively check this one out, especially if it’s on sale.Also buy if you want to murder everyone in your household as a 6-year-old boy."
