76561198098128191,Recommended,218640,19458778,"Posted: 3 December, 2015",all,NIMBLE_JIM,"While very linear and clunky at times, I found this game enjoyable and played it right through to the end despite being very frustrated with it on more than one occasion.  Something about the game made me want to keep on playing, even though it appears unpolished with more than its fair share of bugs. There is something of a charm to this game, the clunky character animations and bad voice acting often made me smile and reminded me of older generation games where things were more basic, so it gave me quite a nostalgic feel.It's a nice idea for a game (depsite the story being obviously copied from The Omen film!), you must play as Lucius, a young boy who is on a mission to reap souls for Lucifer.  To accomplish this, you must guide him around the house, killing 1 person at a time in a variety of creative (and sometimes ridiculous) ways, as another reviewer said, however unrealistic some of the kills are, they always make some sort of logical sense, so you don't feel too cheated if you have been stuck for a while and then accidentally discover the solution. Some of the kills do raise a smile with their creativity!Wait for the mission where you have to catch your uncle in a compromising position with one of the servants - I did laugh out loud when I opened the door!While the game is fully third person free roaming, it is very remeniscent of point and click games of old - 'combine object A with object B and use with interactive object C' etc, so you are very restricted in what you can do and must follow a set order of actions.There are several design issues with the game - often you come across objects that are meant for a mission later on in the game, you try to use them, thinking they are for the current mission, nothing happens so you discount them, only to find out later on in the game you can interact with them, but only when you are meant to.  I feel such objects should not  be accessible at all until they are needed or if they are, there needs to be some explanation for why you cannot use it, or even a 'I don't need this at this time' piece of text.The save system saves the game at the start of each mission stage, but also saves all sub-mission info done after that point.  As a result of this, you often end up with objects in your inventory that you have already used - eg. if you begin a mission, complete one of your chores, then quit out.  When you restart, the chore will already be complete but the character who asked you to do the chore will begin asking you again and the chore item is back in its place. This doesn't break anything, but could be confusing.I did encounter multiple crashes during the first stage of the boss battle at the end, I did however manage to get round it by rushing through once I had worked out how to beat him, still - there seems to be an issue there.To summarise - despite its shortcomings, this is a very enjoyable game and will raise more than a smile or two with its quirk and charm, if you are a fan of point and click - you should find this to your liking."
