76561198376317844,Recommended,218640,32406778,Posted: 14 June,all,humblehero14,"This game is passable to a point that I still recommend it due to its concept, gameplay and story.  There are a lot of problems with the game that needs to be addressed though.First off, the game doesn’t do much in helping you figuring out what to do.  I find myself relying on a walkthrough more times than I want to.  I get an idea on how to go about for the murder but the problem is, I couldn’t find the right item.  The hints don’t help much in guiding you towards the necessary item.In chapter 5,I need a water bottle that located in my room.  Without a guide or random luck, I would be searching for a long time trying to find a mere water bottle in this huge house.  There are even alternative means of filling up water as a substitute and since most of the NPC’s are all in one place, it isn’t hard to go unnoticed.Control mechanics are also problematic if you are using a controller.  I’m not certain if this is a problem using keyboard/mouse though.  The problem is, the control layout is based on Lucius’s POV rather the players POV.  This doesn’t seem to be too much of an issue because there is no combat or the main character isn’t being chased like other games; however, this problem becomes apparent when I’m riding the bike.  I constantly find myself swaying side to side until I realize that it’s on Lucius perspective rather than my perspective.  Since the camera is third person (or second person), the controls should also allow for third person so it won’t feel so wonky.There are tons of clipping issues in this game also.  There was one time I went right through a wall with my bike, in the hallway, where the male marble statue was.  Thankfully, this doesn’t hinder the gameplay much.  Even though there are sneaking elements in the game, I won’t be riding my bike during those times.Voice acting isn’t too much of a problem.  At some points, some voice actors were good.  They felt like they were in the moment.  At other points, it felt like they were just reading a script.  The mother was both good and bad at points.  It felt like she was reading a script early in the game but later when she starts to get frantic, I did felt like I cared for her and hoped that I didn’t have to take her out.The biggest problem is some frame rate issues and the game crashing due to overloading of memory of sorts.  This happened several times especially if I go for that achievement to break glass.  The game starts to lag when you break glass, especially many of them too quickly.  Worst case, you break them in front of many people and they all talk at once thus creating a lag and memory problems.All these gameplay and control mechanics is more than enough to make this unpassable but what pushed it as redeemable is the concept, length of gameplay and storyline.The concept is intriguing.  I, personally, am not the type who enjoys playing the bad guy and killing good guys for no reason, especially mindless violence; however, the idea of “planned murder” is usually intriguing in detective shows.  There are small “quests” the player can do that shows Lucius’s “good side” like do choirs.  Since I’m more of a goody-two-shoes, I enjoy this prolongement before I hurt the ones I love.Sadly, each level is linear and there is only one way to go about each kill.  I guess this is okay because the developers want you to see a kill a certain way.  What’s satisfying is figuring out how Lucius will go about to get his kill.  Again, the frustration is finding exactly where the items are to go about it.There are 18 levels in the game.  The game itself should take anyone between 7 to 15 hours to finish.  Additional time  depends on if your going for the achievements and if your stuck searching the entire house for a specific item.  That’s a good length of time for an indie game.The best part I like was the storyline.  It’s not as great but the idea of “smart” serial killer versus the “smart” detective always strike my fancy.  When you get about halfway through the game and the music starts to change, the drama starts to pick up and my beloved mother is getting more frantic by the level, I am more drawn in and want to see how this all turns out in the end.If you can get through a lot of technical issues with the game, I believe it's still worth playing.  I certainly enjoyed it from beginning to the end."
